<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- M1-M2: Very light opening — 2-note half-note RH (thirds/quartal 4ths), 3-note LH half notes.
  "Rejoices" — joyful but not heavy. "44" quartal I (D-G) gives brightness without weight.
- M3-M4: IV color introduces richness (C3-G3-C4-E4). M4: I whole note — harp resonance peak,
  RH splits into two half-note voicings for gentle inner movement.
- M5-M8: Phrase conclusion. ii→I stepwise bass (A→D→G) at M6 end is the cadential backbone.
  M6 beat 2 uses 3-note RH V chord (F#4-A4-D5) for first time — textural growth.
- M9: Bm-Am second phrase opening — higher register (D5-F#5, C5-E5 in RH), darker chords.
- M10: Arpeggio moment — RH single-note ascending G-B-D arpeggio (eighths then quarters),
  first rhythmic variety away from block chords.
- M11: Descending bass G→D→E in LH across three chords — smooth voice leading.
- M12: V7 whole note + ascending arpeggio RH (D-F#-A-C) = dominant preparation for final section.
  LH V7 full (D-A-C-F#) for maximum dominant tension.
- M13-M14: Same as M5-M6 but 3-note RH voicings throughout — textural increase.
- M15 (climax): Full 3-note RH + 4-note LH every beat, D2 pedal in LH beat 2 (deepest note).
  Quarter-note harmonic rhythm, all voices moving simultaneously.
- M16: Convergence — V half → I half. Final I has 5-note LH (G2-B3-D4) widest spread.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Tenor voice (LH top note) across mm. 1-8: G3→G3→B3→B3→C4→A3→G3→B3→G3 — mostly static
  with brief 3rd motion, provides stability.
- M5-M6 bass: G2→E3→A2→D3→G2 — I→vi→ii→V→I modal chain.
- M12 RH arpeggio: D4→F#4→A4→C5 — V7 spelled out note-by-note for the ear.
- M15 LH deep D2 on beat 2 — deepest note in the arrangement, creates maximum contrast.

TEXTURE ARC:
- M1-M4: Light — half notes, 2-3 voice chords. Open G-major joy.
- M5-M8: Medium — quarter-note motion begins, 3-note RH V chord appears.
